{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"625443b28a61dc4b2849f1934836742e4d9c0c12b7e57ca5e65825a94c8bb2ae","slug":"index","location":"/sections_md/main.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Molecular Understanding of Free Energy Landscapes","keywords":["Molecular Thermodynamics","Free Energy Surfaces","Computational Physical Chemistry","Reaction Coordinates","Machine Learning","Artificial Intelligence"],"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Marcello Sega","given":"Marcello","family":"Sega"},"name":"Marcello Sega","affiliations":["Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London"],"id":"contributors-main-generated-uid-0"},{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Matteo Salvalaglio","given":"Matteo","family":"Salvalaglio"},"name":"Matteo Salvalaglio","email":"m.salvalaglio@ucl.ac.uk","affiliations":["Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London"],"id":"contributors-main-generated-uid-1","corresponding":true}],"affiliations":[{"id":"Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London","name":"Department of Chemical Engineering, University College London"}],"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"main.md","url":"/main-721ba228b00bdb4c7082c9a593ce7b91.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Free energy surfaces (FESs) offer a unifying framework for understanding\nmolecular-level structures, transformations and thermodynamic stability.\nThey distill the complexity of atomistic simulations into interpretable\nlandscapes of metastable states, bridging molecular-level detail with\nmacroscopic observables. This review provides researchers in molecular\nsimulations, computational physical chemistry, and chemical engineering\nwith a conceptual and practical guide to computing and interpreting\nFESs, from their statistical